EXCEPTION - TRS-80 Model III ROM image

The ROM image at public/assets/model3.rom (Model III ROM BASIC) is the
copyrighted firmware of Tandy Corporation / Radio Shack and is NOT covered
by the MIT license above. It is included solely for interoperability so the
emulator can run; the emulator contributors claim no rights over it and
cannot grant any. If you redistribute this repository, the ROM's copyright
remains with its rights holders.









EXCEPTION - Program library game files

The files under public/programs/ are classic TRS-80 software included
solely so the emulator has period software to run. They are NOT covered
by the MIT license above. These titles circulate freely in the TRS-80
preservation community, but the emulator contributors claim no rights
over them and cannot grant any; rights remain with their respective
holders, and any rights holder's removal request will be honored.

From George Phillips's trsjs site (https://trsjs.48k.ca/), where they
are hosted for in-browser play: Super Nova and Galaxy Invasion (Big Five
Software), Sea Dragon (Adventure International), Time Trek, Flying
Saucers, City Defence, Invasion Force, and OPUS-1. (Retro-Zap, also on
trsjs, is deliberately not included: its cassette image uses a custom
encoding this emulator's fast-loader does not support.)

From trs-80.com, Ira Goldklang's TRS-80 software site, added for this
release: Scarfman (Cornsoft, 1981; down-sw-model1.pl?scrfmant.zip),
Defense Command (Big Five, 1982; down-sw-model1.pl?defcmndc.zip), Cosmic
Fighter (Big Five, 1980; down-sw-model3.pl?cosfitr3.zip), Meteor Mission
2 (Big Five, 1981; down-sw-model3.pl?metmiss3.zip), Armored Patrol
(Adventure Intl, 1981; down-sw-model3.pl?armpatl3.zip), Adventureland
(Scott Adams, 1978; down-sw-model3.pl?sa1411c3.zip), and Pirate
Adventure (Scott Adams, 1979; down-sw-model3.pl?sac02408.zip). Scott
Adams has long permitted hobbyist distribution of his classic adventure
games, separately from the general preservation-community basis behind
the rest of this paragraph's titles. Bedlam (Tandy, 1982) is also from
trs-80.com, but from the Model 4 GO-EXEC
distribution (down-sw-model4.pl?bedlamau.zip): BEDLAM.III, the
self-contained Model III payload inside that archive, is the only
digitized copy of Bedlam found, and is what ships here.

Added for v1.5.0, from trs-80.com's download system unless noted:

Wayne Westmoreland and Terry Gilman released their games to the public
domain; their collection readme (in down-sw-model1.pl?westmore.zip)
states: "The programs display copyright notices but I hearby release
them into the public domain, do with them as you please." That covers
Eliminator (down-sw-model3.pl?elimin83.zip), Tank Zone 2000
(down-sw-model3.pl?tankzon3.zip), and Rear Guard
(down-sw-model1.pl?reargrd1.zip, dump 4 of Ira Goldklang's vetted set).

Leo Christopherson's Android Nim, Bee Wary, and Snake Eggs ship from
the 1986 Powersoft/Breeze re-releases (down-sw-model1.pl?andnympw.zip,
beewarps.zip, snkeggps.zip). Each of those archives carries this notice,
retained here as it requires: "Roy Soltoff and/or Bill Schroeder hold
copyright or distribution rights to software and documentation
copyrwritten in the names of Misosys, Logical Systems Inc, Breeze,
Powersoft, and QSD ... Roy and Bill have each granted free permission
to everyone to download and use this software and documentation and to
redistribute it to others, provided this notice is retained. All other
rights are reserved. Kim Watt has also granted free permission to
everyone to download and use any software to which he may hold the
copyright." The shipped .cas files are rebuilt from those releases'
tokenized BASIC by scripts/wrap-tokenized-bas.js (the games' animation
machine code lives inside REM lines and survives via the link chain).

Space Castle (down-sw-model3.pl?spccast3.zip) and Flip-Out
(down-sw-model1.pl?flpoutcg.zip) are Cornsoft Group titles on the same
preservation-community basis as the already-shipped Scarfman. Pyramid
of Doom (down-sw-model3.pl?sac38124.zip) joins under the Scott Adams
note above.

Med Systems' 3-D adventures — Asylum (the self-contained ASYLUM.III
payload of a Model 4 GO-EXEC pack, the same pattern as Bedlam above),
Asylum II, Deathmaze 5000, and Labyrinth — could not be found in
trs-80.com's downloadable set and were sourced from the willus.com Big
List of TRS-80 Software (entries 701, 705, 3268, 7007). No
permission-to-distribute statement from Med Systems or William F.
Denman, Jr. could be located; these ship purely on the
preservation-community basis stated at the top of this exception, and
any rights holder's removal request will be honored immediately. The
circulating Asylum II copy carries a period cracker's modification
notice (Zeta Microcomputer Software) in its header, noted here for
honesty about the dump's provenance.

Titles researched for v1.5.0 and deliberately NOT shipped: Voyage of
the Valkyrie (its downloads on trs-80.com are disabled at the author's
request, honored the same way as Penetrator's below), Dancing Demon,
Duel-N-Droids, and Life Two (no license evidence found and not
downloadable on trs-80.com), Donkey Kong (Westmoreland/Gilman's code is
public domain, but the mark is Nintendo's and the readme itself notes
it was never marketed for that reason), and Zaxxon (written under a
Sega license).

Two titles considered for the v1.3.0 release are not included in
public/programs/. Penetrator (Melbourne House) is on trs-80.com, but
every download of it there has been disabled at the author's request,
which this project honors. Robot Attack has circulating dumps, but no
Model III-compatible copy could be verified running: the Model I
cassette release's protection loader is specific to the Model I ROM,
and the Model III 1500-baud cassette images use an encoding this
emulator's loader does not parse.

Generated locally: sstrek.cas is Super Star Trek from David Ahl's
"BASIC Computer Games" (1978), which Ahl released to the public domain;
the cassette image is built from src/data/super-star-trek.bas by
scripts/build-cas.js. It IS covered by the MIT license above, as are the
BASIC type-in adaptations embedded in src/data/library.js.


EXCEPTION - Bundled disk operating systems (public/disks/)

The three bootable .dsk images under public/disks/ are classic TRS-80
Model III operating systems, included so the emulator's disk hardware
has real software to run. They are NOT covered by the MIT license
above; the emulator contributors claim no rights over them.

ldos-531.dsk (LDOS 5.3.1) is from Tim Mann's MISOSYS archive
(https://tim-mann.org/misosys.html, trs80/ld3-531.zip). The source zip
embeds this notice, retained as it requires: "Roy Soltoff and/or
William Schroeder hold copyright and/or distribution rights to the
software and documentation in this ZIP archive. Roy Soltoff and William
Schroeder each individually grant free permission to everyone to
download and use this software and documentation and to redistribute it
to others, provided this notice is retained. All other rights are
reserved."

trsdos13.dsk (TRSDOS 1.3, Tandy, 1981) is from the willus.com Big List
of TRS-80 Software (entry 14364, TDOS13A.DSK). It is Tandy/Radio Shack
firmware-era software included on the same interoperability basis as
the Model III ROM exception above: the disk subsystem cannot be
meaningfully used without a DOS, rights remain with the rights holders,
and any removal request will be honored.

newdos80.dsk (NEWDOS/80 v2, Apparat Inc.) is from the willus.com Big
List (entry 9601, NWDS80-3.DSK — a working system disk, volume name
SPOCK-22). It circulates freely in the TRS-80 preservation community;
no formal permission statement is known, rights remain with the rights
holders, and any removal request will be honored.
